Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

When hot, add the @British pork mince{240%g} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook until browned, ~{4-5%mins}. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

While the pork is browning, halve peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced).

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%500g can} in a #sieve{}.

Once the pork is browned, stir in the onion. Cook with the pork mince until softened, ~{4-5%mins}.

Stir in the garlic, @pasanda style seasoning{1}(use less if you don't like spice), @tomato puree{30%g} and @ginger puree{1}.

Combine and cook for ~{1%minute}, then pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @water{150%ml} and @chicken stock powder{1}.

Stir in the lentils, bring to the boil and simmer until the mixture has reduced slightly, ~{3-4%mins}.

Meanwhile, trim the @spring onion{1} and thinly slice.

Stir the @chopped kale{100%g} into the pork mixture in handfuls.

Cover with a #lid{} or some #tin foil{} and simmer until the kale is tender, ~{3-4%mins}.

Meanwhile, pop the @plain naans{2} into your oven to warm through, ~{3-4%mins}.

Taste the curry and add salt and pepper if you feel it needs it.

> TIP: Add a splash of water too if the liquid has evaporated too much.

Serve in #bowls{} with the spring onion sprinkled over the top and the naan on the side for mopping up the curry! Enjoy!